-- Strong Induction (Complete Induction)
--
-- Classical: Assume P(0)...P(n-1) to prove P(n)
-- CredTT: Same degradation issues as regular induction
--         Plus: accessing all previous cases multiplies credences
--
-- Example: Every integer > 1 has a prime factor
-- Use: If n is prime, done. If composite, n = ab with a,b < n.
--      By strong IH, a has prime factor, which is also prime factor of n.

-- Classical strong induction: use ALL previous cases
-- CredTT strong induction: credence depends on how many cases used

-- Strong IH: forall k < n. P(k) @ c_k
-- Want to prove: P(n) @ ?

-- If we use P(k1), P(k2), ..., P(km) in the proof:
-- Each use multiplies: c_{k1} * c_{k2} * ... * c_{km}

postulate base : P_0 @ 1
postulate strong_step : strong_IH_to_P_n @ 1

-- If step uses just ONE previous case:
-- Same as regular induction: c_n = c_0 * step^n

-- If step uses TWO previous cases (like Fibonacci):
-- P(n) uses P(n-1) and P(n-2)
-- c_n = c_{n-1} * c_{n-2} * step

-- If step @ 1 and we use 2 cases:
-- c_n = c_{n-1} * c_{n-2}
-- This is like Fibonacci but for credences!
-- Even starting at c_0 = c_1 = 1, we have c_n = 1 for all n

-- If step @ 0.99 and uses 2 cases:
-- c_n = c_{n-1} * c_{n-2} * 0.99
-- Degradation is FASTER than linear!

-- BOUNDED STRONG INDUCTION:
-- Use at most k previous cases
-- Degradation bounded by k * step per level

-- WHY STRONG INDUCTION DIFFERS:
-- Regular: linear degradation
-- Strong (unbounded): potentially exponential degradation
-- Strong (bounded): controlled degradation

-- The KEY insight:
-- Classical strong induction is FREE (use any previous case)
-- CredTT strong induction COSTS (each use multiplies)

-- This is why well-founded induction matters:
-- The well-founded order constrains which cases you can use
-- CredTT tracks the cost of this access
